==This is the [[:en:Akan_languages|Akan]]-language Wikipedia.==
If you speak Akan, or any of the Akan dialects (Akuapim, Asante, Kwawu, Akyem, Wassa, Nsemaa, Ahanta, Baule, Fante, Gomua, Bono, Twi, etc.), please click "edit" and help write it. Please, let's try to work together on a common Akan Wikipedia. We do not yet have the critical mass to start separate Wikipedias in all the dialects.

Important Note on Akan Dialects: Akan is somehow synonymous with Twi, where the former represents the Ethnic group and the latter their language. (Please note that the Fante do not consider themselves as part of the broader Twi alliance).  There are some variations in spelling, pronunciation, tone, stress, etc. Besides mainstream Twi, the most easily recognizable and distinct Akan forms are Fante and Akuapem. Akuapem, however, is an important component of Twi, given their polite socio-linguistic forms and early vocation as educators and religious instructors under the tutelage of the Basel Mission.

Akuapem Twi has a slow pitch, making their speakers sound eloquent. Akans who speak Fante have perculiar ways of "distinguishing" themselves from the Twi, both intentionally and of course, naturally.  It is very unusual, except for those with a deeper knowledge of the various Akan dialects, to distinguish between the Asante, Akyem, Kwawu, Akwamu, Wassa, etc. forms. The only major marker here pertains to specific given names. Example: 1. Soup Laddle-(N)kwankorowa, (N)kwan Ta.  1. Home-Ofie, Efie 3. Kitchen-Gyaade, Mukaase, etc, etc. The trained ear then quickly picks out the difference, and tries to establish if the speaker is Akyem, Asante or Kwawu. 

Another comment worthy of note is that some Twi speakers do have a secondary "language" which mainstream Akan speakers cannot comprehend. I use language because to speak of these entirely different patterns as "dialects" is erroneous. If these were dialects, then all Twi speakers would be able to understand them. Examples are Nzemah, Ahanta, Kyerepon and Bono. These are thoroughbred Akans with a "spare" language. If a Bono or Kyerepon decides to divert from Twi, only their natives can follow the conversation. The same happens in Nzemah and Ahanta. The Asante or Akuapem is not be able to follow an Ahanta or Nzemah discourse. On the contrary, Akyem, Fante, Kwawu, Akuapem and Asante speakers are fully understood by this special group.

